## 4. Full Example (Minimal Stand‑Alone Test)

If you want to compile and run a **stand‑alone** demonstration (no MAPS‑Multi harness), the following `main.cpp` shows how to use the library:

```cpp
// main.cpp  (stand‑alone demo, not part of the required answer)
#include <cstdio>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <vector>
#include <cuda_runtime.h>
#include "gol_host.cpp"   // pulls in launch_gol_update

int main()
{
    const uint32_t rows = 64, cols = 64;
    const size_t N = rows * cols;

    // Simple glider pattern (alive = 1, dead = 0)
    std::vector<uint8_t> input(N, 0);
    input[ 5*cols + 6] = 1;
    input[ 6*cols + 7] = 1;
    input[ 7*cols + 5) = 1;
    input[ 7*cols + 6] = 1;
    input[ 7*cols + 7] = 1;

    // Output buffer (host memory, one contiguous array)
    std::vector<uint8_t> output(N);

    // Run the update on all GPUs
    launch_gol_update(input.data(),
                      output.data(),
                      rows, cols,
                      false);   // do NOT write PNG in this demo

    // Print a few cells to verify the update
    for (uint32_t y = 0; y < rows; ++y) {
        for (uint32_t x = 0; x < cols; ++x) {
            printf("%d ", output[y*cols + x]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Compile with:

```bash
nvcc -arch=sm_70 -O3 -o gol_demo main.cpp -ldl
./gol_demo
```

You should see the glider pattern evolve according to Life’s rules.

